This shows one of the ways in which the factory would cover up the spoiled meat and sell it. Some other ways included putting meat with dirt and rust from waste barrels and mixing it with fresh meat. "Every spring they did it; and in the barrels would be dirt and rust and old nails and stale water - and cartload after cartload of it would be taken up and dumped into the hoppers with fresh meat, and sent out to the public's breakfast." This shows some of the ways in which the meatpacking industry had hidden spoiled meat from the public.
column4: When the factory received spoiled meat, they sought to avoid waste and maintain profit margins. Their methods involved concealing spoiled meat by adding chemicals or covering it with dirt and rust. These practices were employed to deceive consumers and maintain a seemingly legitimate supply of meat when it was unfit for consumption.

column3: The factory would rub the meat in soda to take away the smell, and pump ham into a strong-smelling pickle. Meatpackers would extract the bone of spoiled ham and insert in the hole a white-hot iron.  Skinned hams made of old hogs were cooked and chopped up into cheese. When rats got into them, they would poison them with bread; the bread would get packed into the meat, along with the rats.
